<p>The <a href="/projects/1/care-plans-authoring">Authoring tool</a> allows doctors to efficiently create Care Plans. But after creating and assigning it to patients, how can they actually keep track of patients' progresses outside the hospital?</p>

<p>The management tool, used by case managers or patient care team, monitors patient activities. In critical situations, the tool would alert and escalate the issue.</p>

<p>My goal in this project was to create the beta version of the management tool for the case managers.</p>

<div class="project-detail-divider"></div>

<h2>Target Users</h2>

<h4>Case managers</h4>
<p>Case managers monitor patients' activities in their Care Plans and triage them.</p>

<p>When a patient enrolls in a Care Plan, all of his or her activities in the Care Plan are captured by the Care Plans system. As described in the <a href="/projects/1/care-plans-authoring">Authoring tool</a> write up, a Care Plan is a collection of triggers and actions. For example, if a patient with Type 2 Diabetes' fasting glucose level is very high (trigger), he should talk to a doctor (action). But sometimes it shouldn't be the patient's sole responsibility to take action. It helps if the doctor is notified of it as well so that he can encourage the patient to come in for a visit. This is where case managers come in. When a Care Plan triggers an action, case managers are notified of it, so that they can triage the activity as needed.</p>

<h4>Case management directors</h4>
<p>Case management directors are responsible for assigning Care Plans to case managers and overseeing all enrolled patients' progress across different Care Plans.</p>

