<p>The initial wireframes were well received by our partner's board, who were impressed with the metrics and compliance rate visualizations.</p>

<h4>Problems with "fancy" data visualizations</h4>
<p>Although well received by our partner's board members, after reviewing the designs with our actual target users, it was clear that the colorfully decorated diagrams and graphs did not provide much value to them.</p>

<p>Interviews with doctors and case managers showed that:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The visualizations not only did not help with their workflows, it wasn't even feasible because this model assumes that a large number of population would be assigned to the same Care Plan (so that the visualizations can be created per Care Plan)</li>
  <li>Case managers pointed out that they each only work with a few patients</li>
  <li>Doctors noted that it was impossible and inefficient to prescribe a single Care Plan to a large population, as patients' conditions differ and require different monitoring and treatment</li>
</ul>

<p>The only suitable metric to compare among patients was the compliance rate. So all other visualizations were removed. I started to work more closely with our actual target users and iterated.</p>

<h4>Back to the drawing board...</h4>

<p>Our partner already had a group of case managers working with a few patients in managing their acute conditions. I was able to survey them and understand their day-to-day tasks and needs. Their workflow was actually very similar to that of JIRA or Trello, which was triaging issues and managing tasks.</p>

<p>Based on a series of interviews with case managers, I created new iterations that reflected and supported their workflow.</p>

